[[File:GrandCayman.jpg|thumb|right|Map of Grand Cayman]] [[File:Caribbean Elaenia.jpg|thumb|right|The Eastern Dry Forest is an important site for Caribbean elaenias]]
The '''Eastern Dry Forest''' lies at the eastern end of [[Grand Cayman]], one of the [[Cayman Islands]], a [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] in the [[Caribbean Sea]]. It is one of the territory’s [[Important Bird Area]]s (IBAs).
==Description== Eastern Dry Forest is a 239&nbsp;ha tract of native [[Tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests|tropical dry forest]] lying north of the town of East End. The only area of dry forest left at the eastern end of the island, it is privately owned, unprotected and is subject to [[deforestation|clearance]] and fragmentation. In the 1980s the site contained some of the largest trees on the island and was an important breeding site for parrots.<ref name=bli/>
===Birds=== The IBA was identified as such by [[BirdLife International]] because it supports populations of [[Cuban amazon]]s, [[Caribbean elaenia]]s, [[thick-billed vireo]]s, [[Yucatan vireo]]s and [[vitelline warbler]]s.<ref name=bli>{{cite web |url=http://www.birdlife.org |title=Eastern Dry Forest |accessdate=2014-04-01 |work=Important Bird Areas factsheet |first= |last= |publisher=BirdLife International |year=2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5QE8rvIqH?url=http://www.birdlife.org/ |archivedate=2007-07-10 |df= }}</ref>
